'''Axel Tuanzebe''' (born 14 November 1997) is a Congolese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for {{English football updater|Burnley}} club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and the [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo national team]].

Tuanzebe is a graduate of the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United youth system]] and won both the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy#Players of the Year|Jimmy Murphy Young Player of the Year]] and Denzil Haroun Reserve Team Player of the Year awards. He made his competitive debut in an [[FA Cup]] game against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in January 2017. He had three spells on loan at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and helped them to win promotion to the Premier League in 2019. After spending time with [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] in 2022 and [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in 2023, he was released by Manchester United at the end of the 2022–23 season. Following two seasons at [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], with whom he won promotion to the Premier League, he joined Burnley on a free transfer.

Born in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Tuanzebe relocated to England at a young age and represented England at [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]], [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels, before opting to represent the DR Congo senior team in 2024.

==Club career==
===Manchester United===
====Early years====
[[File:Manchester United v Wigan Athletic, January 2017 (33).JPG|thumb|upright|Tuanzebe playing for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 2017]]

Tuanzebe was associated with the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United academy]] from the age of eight.<ref name=manutdprofile>{{cite web |title=Axel Tuanzebe player profile page |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/players-and-staff/detail/axel-tuanzebe |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref> He was captain of the [[SuperCupNI|Milk Cup]] winning youth side in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=4 Manchester United youngsters who look destined for the first team |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/4-manchester-united-youngsters-who-look-destined-first-team |publisher=FourFourTwo |date=16 November 2016 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref> In May 2015, Tuanzebe won the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy#Players of the Year|Jimmy Murphy Young Player of the Year]] award.<ref name=jmaward>{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Mathieson |title=David de Gea: I love Manchester United colleagues and fans are best in the world |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/david-de-gea-love-manchester-9289131 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=19 May 2015 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref> Academy coach [[Paul McGuinness (footballer)|Paul McGuinness]] noted that Tuanzebe was likely the first first-year scholar to captain the under-18 side since [[Gary Neville]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Who is Axel Tuanzebe? Profile of Manchester United youngster on loan with Aston Villa |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/who-is-axel-tuanzebe-wiki-11620920 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=15 March 2018 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref>

On 31 October 2015, at the age of 17, Tuanzebe was named on the substitutes bench for a match against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in the [[Premier League]], the first time he had been a member of a first-team matchday squad.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alistair |last=Magowan |title=Crystal Palace 0–0 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34623912 |website=BBC Sport |date=31 October 2015 |access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester United manager Van Gaal explains why he named Tuanzebe in Crystal Palace squad |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-united-manager-van-gaal-10403525 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=7 November 2015 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref>

====2016–17 season====
On 29 January 2017, Tuanzebe made his Manchester United debut as a 68th-minute substitute, replacing [[Timothy Fosu-Mensah]] during a 4–0 [[2016–17 FA Cup|FA Cup]] victory over [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United 4–0 Wigan Athletic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38709050 |website=BBC Sport |date=29 January 2017 |access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref> Four days later, he extended his contract at Manchester United until 2020, with the option of a further year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Axel Tuanzebe signs new Manchester United contract |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/10753590/axel-tuanzebe-signs-new-manchester-united-contract |publisher=Sky Sports |date=2 February 2017 |access-date=2 February 2017}}</ref> On 7 May 2017, Tuanzebe started a senior match for the first time, in a 2–0 defeat against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |first=Samuel |last=Lovett |title=Manchester United's Axel Tuanzebe 'chuffed' after making full debut and taking on Arsenal's Alexis Sanchez |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/manchester-united-news-axel-tuanzebe-full-debut-chuffed-taking-on-alexis-sanchez-a7724446.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=8 May 2017 |access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> He won the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy#Players of the Year|Denzil Haroun Reserve Team Player of the Year]] award in May 2017.<ref name=dhaward>{{cite news |first=Samuel |last=Luckhurst |title=Manchester United player Ander Herrera wins Player of the Year award|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-united-news-ander-herrera-13058295 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=18 May 2017 |access-date=19 May 2017}}</ref>

====2017–18 season====
Tuanzebe made his first start of the season against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] in the [[2017–18 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] on 24 October 2017, playing a key part in the second goal of the 2–0 victory.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dafydd |last=Pritchard |title=Swansea City 0–2 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41647091 |website=BBC Sport |date=24 October 2017 |access-date=30 October 2017}}</ref> On 5 December 2017, he made his European debut in a 2–1 victory over [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] in the [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Hafez |last=Shamoon |title=Manchester United 2–1 CSKA Moscow |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42229382|website=BBC Sport |access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>

====Loans to Aston Villa====
On 25 January 2018, Tuanzebe joined [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Villa sign Man Utd defender Tuanzebe |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42818253 |website=BBC Sport |date=25 January 2018 |access-date=25 January 2018 }}</ref> However, due to injury problems and the form of preferred centre-backs [[James Chester]] and [[John Terry]] he was only able to make five appearances before returning to Manchester United.<ref>{{cite news |title=Axel Tuanzebe: Aston Villa re-sign Manchester United defender on loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45084058 |work=BBC Sport |date=6 August 2018 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref> In August 2018, after going on United's pre-season tour to the United States, he joined Aston Villa on loan again for the [[2018–19 AVFC season|2018–19 season]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United centre-back Axel Tuanzebe joins Aston Villa on loan |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11677/11463457/manchester-united-centre-back-axel-tuanzebe-joins-aston-villa-on-loan |publisher=Sky Sports |date=6 August 2018 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref> On 27 May 2019, he played the full 90 minutes as Villa achieved promotion to the Premier League in the [[2019 EFL Championship play-off final]] with a victory over [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] in the final.<ref name=playoff>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48331145 |title=Aston Villa 2–1 Derby County |first=Ian |last=Woodcock |website=BBC Sport |date=27 May 2019 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref>

====2019–20 season====
In July 2019, Tuanzebe signed a new contract with Manchester United until June 2022, with an option for an additional year.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48882567 |title=Manchester United: Andreas Pereira and Axel Tuanzebe sign new contracts |work=BBC Sport |date=5 July 2019 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref> At 21 years old, he became the youngest player to captain United since [[Norman Whiteside]] in 1985, during an EFL Cup victory against [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] in September 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/axel-tuanzebe-man-utd-captain-16986869 |title=Ole Gunnar Solskjaer explains why Axel Tuanzebe captained Manchester United |work=Manchester Evening News |date=26 September 2019 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref> Throughout the first two months of the 2019–20, Tuanzebe established himself as a starting centre back for Manchester United and was due to start the [[North West Derby]] in October but suffered a hip injury in the warm up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/manchester-united-v-liverpool-20-october-premier-league-match-report|title=Manchester United v Liverpool 20 October Premier League match report &#124; Manchester United}}</ref> He made his return in December's EFL Cup victory over [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]], but suffered a [[hamstring]] injury during the game ruling him out for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-man-utd-v-colchester-carabao-cup-quarter-final|title=Man Utd 3 Colchester 0|publisher=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref>

====2020–21 season====
On 20 October 2020, Tuanzebe started his first game in 10 months, after suffering an ankle injury in pre-season. The game was his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut in which Manchester United won 2–1 away against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-paris-saint-germain-v-man-utd-20-october-2020|title=Match report: PSG 1 Man Utd 2|publisher=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref> Tuanzebe received praise for his match performance, especially his defensive work against [[Kylian Mbappé]] and [[Neymar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/how-axel-tuanzebe-delivered-a-flawless-return-to-first-team-action-in-man-united-win-against-psg|title=How Axel Tuanzebe delivered a flawless return to action against PSG &#124; Manchester United}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=21 October 2020|title=Why Axel Tuanzebe's performance in Paris should not come as a surprise|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/psg-vs-manchester-united-axel-tuanzebe-champions-league-b1193025.html|access-date=2021-01-31|website=The Independent|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/manchester-united-2-1-psg-tuanzebe-solskajers-unlikely-hero-2020-10 | title=A forgotten 22-year-old who hasn't played in nearly a year was the unlikely star as Manchester United produced a shock Champions League win over PSG | website=[[Business Insider]] }}</ref> He started his first league game of the season on 27 January 2021, in a 2–1 home defeat to eventual bottom-finishers [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-united-v-sheffield-utd-27-january-2021|title=Match report: Manchester United 1 Sheffield Utd 2 &#124; Manchester United}}</ref> On 25 February, he scored what would have been his only goal for Manchester United in the [[UEFA Europa League]] against [[Real Sociedad]]. However, VAR ruled the goal put due to teammate [[Victor Lindelöf]] fouling an opponent during the corner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-man-utd-v-real-sociedad-europa-league-last-32-second-leg-25-feb-2021|title=Report: United 0 Real Sociedad 0|publisher=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref> Tuanzebe played all remaining Europa League games up until and including the final and was a rotation option in the Premier League making 19 appearances in total.

====2021–22 season: Aston Villa & Napoli loans====
After a couple of displays for Manchester United in pre season friendlies, including a 4–2 away defeat at [[Queens Park Rangers]], on 8 August 2021, Tuanzebe signed a new two-year contract with Manchester United, with the option of an extra year; that day, he also agreed to rejoin Aston Villa on loan for the 2021–22 season, his third loan spell with the club.<ref>{{cite news |first=Harry |last=Robinson |title=Tuanzebe signs new deal and goes on loan |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/axel-tuanzebe-signs-new-man-utd-contract-and-joins-aston-villa-on-loan |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=8 August 2021 |accessdate=8 August 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58138444|title=Aston Villa re-sign Tuanzebe on loan|work=BBC Sport |date=8 August 2021 }}</ref> On 8 January 2022, Tuanzebe was recalled from his Aston Villa loan, and loaned to [[Serie A]] team [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Il Napoli ufficializza l'arrivo di Tuanzebe con la formula del prestito|url=https://www.sscnapoli.it/static/news/Il-Napoli-ufficializza-l-acquisto-di-Tuanzebe-con-la-formula-del-prestito-24341.aspx|access-date=8 January 2022|date=8 January 2022|website=sscnapoli.it |publisher=S.S.C. Napoli|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New loan move for Tuanzebe |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/axel-tuanzebe-moves-to-napoli-on-loan-until-end-of-2021-22-season |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |access-date=8 January 2022 |date=8 January 2022}}</ref>

====2022–23 season: Stoke City loan====
Tuanzebe suffered a further injury in the pre-season of 2022–23 season and did not return to training until January. On deadline day of the mid-season transfer window, he joined [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on loan for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tuanzebe makes it five |url=https://www.stokecityfc.com/news/2023/february/01/tuanzebe-makes-it-five/ |website=Stoke City |date=February 2023 |access-date=1 February 2023}}</ref> However, continued injury problems restricted him to only five appearances.<ref>{{cite web |title=Easy Man United contract decision is complicated one for Stoke City |url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/stoke-manchester-united-axel-tuanzebe-8401484 |website=Stoke Sentinel |date=May 2023 |access-date=10 May 2023}}</ref>

===Ipswich Town===
On 8 September 2023, Tuanzebe signed for [[EFL Championship]] side [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on an initial 12-month contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2023/september/08/town-sign-tuanzebe/ | date = 8 September 2023 | access-date = 8 September 2023 | publisher = Ipswich Town F.C. | title = Town sign Tuanzebe}}</ref> He made his debut for the club in a 3–1 [[2023–24 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] loss to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 1 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12997265/ipswich-1-3-fulham-premier-league-side-ease-past-championship-high-flyers-to-reach-carabao-cup-quarter-finals|title=Ipswich 1–3 Fulham: Premier League side ease past Championship high-flyers to reach Carabao Cup quarter-finals|date=1 November 2023|access-date=28 April 2025|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> Six days later, he made his league debut in a 2–2 draw with [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67333369|title=Rotherham 2–2 Ipswich: Christ Tiehi strike snatches draw for Millers|date=7 November 2023|access-date=28 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 6 January 2024, Tuanzebe scored his first goal for Ipswich in a 3–1 win over [[AFC Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] in the third round of the [[2023–24 FA Cup|FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/sport/24032074.ipswich-town-seal-fa-cup-progression-3-1-win-afc-wimbledon/|title=Ipswich Town seal FA Cup progression with 3–1 win at AFC Wimbledon|date=6 January 2024|access-date=28 April 2025|website=Ipswich Star}}</ref>

During the second half of the [[2023–24 Ipswich Town F.C. season|2023–24 season]], Tuanzebe established himself as Ipswich's starting right-back as the club gained promotion back to the Premier League after a 22-year absence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/players/axeltuanzebe/|title=40 Axel Tuanzebe|access-date=28 April 2025|publisher=Ipswich Town F.C.}}</ref>

On 3 June 2024, Ipswich announced they had extended his contract by 12 months.<ref>{{Cite web |last=FC |first=Ipswich Town |date=3 June 2024 |title=RETAINED LIST CONFIRMED |url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2024/june/03/ipswich-town-retained-list-summer-2024/ |access-date=2024-06-06 |website=Ipswich Town FC |language=en}}</ref> In October 2024 he suffered an unusual injury when he cut his thumb while washing dishes, requiring surgery to save it.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/oct/08/ipswich-axel-tuanzebe-layoff-after-freak-accident-while-washing-up|title=Ipswich's Axel Tuanzebe faces layoff after freak accident while washing up|author=Nick Ames|date=8 October 2024|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>

===Burnley===
On 26 June 2025, following Ipswich Town's relegation from Premier League, Tuanzebe joined newly-promoted [[Premier League]] side [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cq8z02xze8do|title=Burnley sign Tuanzebe on free transfer from Ipswich|publisher=BBC|date=26 June 2025|accessdate=27 June 2025}}</ref> He scored his first Premier League goal in a 2–2 draw with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on 24 January 2026.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://burnleyfootballclub.com/content/talking-points-post-tottenham-hotspur-h-tuanzebe |title=TALKING POINTS POST TOTTENHAM HOTSPUR (H): TUANZEBE |publisher=Burnley F.C. |date=24 January 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
===England===
Tuanzebe was eligible to represent England or the Democratic Republic of the Congo at international level.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolasie & Abraham can fire Aston Villa back to the Premier League |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/aston-villa/story/3632573/bolasie-and-abraham-can-fire-aston-villa-back-to-the-premier-league |publisher=ESPN |date=14 September 2018 |access-date=23 October 2020}}</ref> He played youth international football for England at [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]], [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Axel Tuanzebe |url=https://www.besoccer.com/player/a-tuanzebe-289789 |website=besoccer.com |access-date=1 February 2023}}</ref>

Tuanzebe began his international career in June 2016, when he made his first appearance for England at under-19 level, against Mexico.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Marshall |title=Tuanzebe primed for first international tournament with England |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2016/Jun/young-manchester-united-defender-axel-tuanzebe-first-international-tournament-with-england-under-19s.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=7 June 2016 |access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref> He was a member of the England under-20 squad which won all three matches at the Four Nations tournament in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=England Under-20s win mini-tournament after 2–0 win over USA |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2016/oct/10/england-u20s-2-0-usa-report-101016 |publisher=The Football Association |date=10 October 2016 |access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref> Tuanzebe was withdrawn from selection for the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] due to club commitments.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man United's Axel Tuanzebe left out of England U20 World Cup squad|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/manchester-united/story/3121904/manchester-uniteds-axel-tuanzebe-left-out-of-england-u20-world-cup-squad |publisher=ESPN |date=8 May 2017 |access-date=14 April 2018}}</ref>

On 10 November 2017, Tuanzebe made his debut for England at under-21 level, against [[Ukraine national under-21 football team|Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine U21 0–2 England U21|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41884793 |website=BBC Sport |date=10 November 2017 |access-date=14 April 2018}}</ref>

===DR Congo===
In December 2023, Tuanzebe was pre-called up by the [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo national team]] for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web |title=AFCON 2023 – PROVISIONAL SQUADS LIST|url=https://www.cafonline.com/media/szzh20fx/afcon-2023-provisional-squads-list.pdf|page=11}}</ref>

Tuanzebe made his debut for the [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo national team]] on 6 June 2024 in a [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF Group B|World Cup qualifier]] against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] at the [[Diamniadio Olympic Stadium]]. He played the full match as the game ended in a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=ESPN|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/687145/|title=Senegal v DR Congo game report|date=6 June 2024}}</ref>

On 31 March 2026, Tuanzebe scored his first senior international goal in a 1–0 extra-time win over [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|2026 World Cup qualification inter-confederation play-offs]], securing his nation's first World Cup appearance since 1974.<ref>{{cite web |last=Williams |first=Ian |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cn43qqy9z8xo |title=Tuanzebe sends DR Congo back to World Cup after 52 years |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2026 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
Tuanzebe's preferred position is at [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]], but he can also play as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right-back]], and has featured as a [[Midfielder#Holding midfielder|holding midfielder]].<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Ducker |title=Axel Tuanzebe out of England U-20 squad as Mourinho wants him to play more for Man Utd |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/05/09/axel-tuanzebe-england-u-20-squad-mourinho-wants-play-man-utd/ |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=9 May 2017 |access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Marshall |title=Axel Tuanzebe is coming of age at United |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Features/2017/May/axel-tuanzebe-if-you-are-good-enough-you-are-old-enough.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=25 May 2017 |access-date=30 October 2017}}</ref> His playing style has been compared to that of his former Manchester United teammate [[Eric Bailly]] and former [[Spain national football team|Spain]] international [[Javi Martínez]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Tighe |title=Manchester United's Axel Tuanzebe Has Hallmarks of Eric Bailly and Javi Martinez |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2663571-manchester-uniteds-axel-tuanzebe-has-hallmarks-of-eric-bailly-and-javi-martinez |work=Bleacher Report |publisher=Turner |date=14 September 2016 |access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref> Tuanzebe's performance on his first-team debut in a friendly against Wigan Athletic in July 2016 led manager [[José Mourinho]] to remark, "10 minutes is enough! The potential is there, you see it immediately."<ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Bajkowski |title=Mourinho praises Manchester United youngster Tuanzebe for his EIGHT minutes against Wigan |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-united-axel-tuanzebe-mourinho-11624047 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=16 July 2016 |access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Tuanzebe was born in [[Bunia]], in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.<ref name=Soccerway/> He emigrated to England with his family in 2002.<ref>{{cite news |date=26 January 2018 |title=Manchester United starlet Axel Tuanzebe out to prove he has come of age during Aston Villa loan |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/aston-villa/2018/01/26/manchester-united-starlet-axel-tuanzebe-out-to-prove-he-has-come-of-age-during-aston-villa-loan/ |access-date=23 October 2020 |work=Express & Star}}</ref> He attended [[St Cuthbert's RC High School]] in [[Rochdale]] and captained the Year 7 football team to the final of the English National Schools Cup at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in 2009.<ref name="earlylife">{{cite news |last=Luckhurst |first=Samuel |date=11 November 2015 |title=Manchester United youngster Axel Tuanzebe 'born for greatness' |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-united-youngster-axel-tuanzebe-10396435 |access-date=15 November 2016 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> In the same year, he was awarded Sports Boy of the Year by the Mayor of Rochdale.<ref name=earlylife/> He also represented his school in cross-country and triple-jump.<ref name=earlylife/> He is the younger brother of ex-[[Clitheroe F.C.|Clitheroe]] striker Dimitri Tuanzebe.<ref>{{cite news |last=Luckhurst |first=Samuel |date=29 January 2017 |title=Who is Axel Tuanzebe? Manchester United youngster in profile |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/who-is-axel-tuanzebe-united-11620920 |access-date=30 January 2017 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News}}</ref>

In July 2018, Tuanzebe broke the Guinness World Record for the fastest time to individually clear a game of [[Hungry Hungry Hippos]], while in Los Angeles on Manchester United's pre-season tour.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dunker |first=Charlotte |date=18 July 2018 |title=Axel Tuanzebe breaks bizarre Guinness World Record on Manchester United pre-season tour |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/man-utd-tuanzebe-world-record-14923653 |access-date=19 July 2018 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fastest time to clear a game of Hungry Hungry Hippos (individual) |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/431869-fastest-time-to-clear-a-game-of-hungry-hungry-hippos-individual |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113161229/https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/431869-fastest-time-to-clear-a-game-of-hungry-hungry-hippos-individual/ |archive-date=13 November 2020 |access-date=23 October 2020 |publisher=Guinness World Records}}</ref> The record has since been broken.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Fastest time to clear a game of Hungry Hungry Hippos (individual) |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/431869-fastest-time-to-clear-a-game-of-hungry-hungry-hippos-individual |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250118003213/https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/431869-fastest-time-to-clear-a-game-of-hungry-hungry-hippos-individual |archive-date=18 January 2025 |access-date=2025-12-23 |website=Guinness World Records |language=en-GB |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2025, Tuanzebe sued Manchester United for alleged negligent medical advice. The claim related to a value of over £1 million, from a period between July 2022 and his loan to Stoke the following January.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mashiter |first1=Nick |last2=Stone |first2=Simon |title=Defender Tuanzebe sues former club Man Utd |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c04d25r24vyo |access-date=14 July 2025 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

